description: Honorably served in the U.S. Army for approximately 20 years and six months as a school trained Counterintelligence (CI) Agent with both strategic and tactical experience, serving in various military units, supporting Conventional and Special Forces units. School trained in CFSO/ LLSO source operations, surveillance/counter-surveillance. Previous experience in source operations while deployed to Bosnia-Herzegovina and most recent experience while deployed to Iraq and Afghanistan. Knowledgeable of the intelligence cycle, intelligence community databases and search tools (i.e. SIPRnet, NIPRnet, Palantir platform, Biometrics Automated Toolset (BAT/ HIIDE, SEEK), TIGR, CIDNE, M3, TAC, DSOMS, Falconview, DCGS-A QuerryTree, BI2R and SOFEX) required to obtain intelligence data and conduct research/analysis. Resourceful individual who is professional, flexible, and dedicated to mission accomplishment and possesses the ability to work under pressure in a high stress, high threat, time sensitive environment without supervision.

description: Open Source Intelligence Subject Matter Expert at the US Army Headquarters-Intelligence Division G2. Implements and understands Open-Source Intelligence laws, regulations, and policies. Develop and creates the open-source and social media architecture and tools. Develop policies and guidance on Social Media and its OSINT implications. Utilize DCGS-A. Implements OSINT policies and guidance with the Intelligence Community, especially as it relates to OSINT. - Open-Source Intelligence laws, regulations, and policies. - Open-source and social media architecture and tools. - Work closely with the participants of the open-source community. - Work with the Army and Joint staff. - Develop and creates policies and guidance on Army DOMEX policies, guidance and regulations. - Represent the Army at National and below meetings and briefings regarding all facets of Open-Source and DOMEX. - Work hand in hand with the Joint and Service military structure/organization. - Prepare and submits OSINT policies and documentation for staff actions.

description: Intelligence Analyst supporting US Army G2 utilizing Army ISR asset to research, develop, and present enterprise architecture artifacts in DoDAF format and analysis in support of PEO IEW&S stated requirements. Provides direct customer support while addressing current and future issues, concepts and requirements addressing Army systems, capabilities, functions, disciplines, and organizations. Participates in various process teams and ad hoc groups in support of Army related system requirements, operational and organizational plans and concepts, and technical, system, and operational architectures. Extensive experience with Army Intelligence Surveillance and Reconnaissance assets and systems. Knowledge of Army Capabilities and Functions and Operational Architectures, CONOPS as a document of guidance. Knowledgeable in the Army Acquisition Process. Solid understanding of the DoD Architecture Framework (DoDAF), Federal Enterprise Architecture Framework (FEAF) and C4ISR Architecture Framework.

description: Worked as the primary OSINT instructor/trainer developer for USCENTCOM J2 Regional Joint Intelligence Training and Education Facility (RJITEF). In charge of developing lesson plans, practical exercise scenarios, program of instructions, test evaluations and piloting multiple lessons incorporating open source research, social network collection and analysis which include cyber activities, virtual hacker's activities and adversarial website exploitation. Created the first USCENTCOM Open Source Analysis course. Develop open source training materials for military audience caters to USCENTCOM area of operations (AO). Develop Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) products in support of Human Intelligence (HUMINT), Signals Intelligence (SIGINT), Imagery Intelligence (IMINT), Measures and Assessment Intelligence (MASINT) and Geospatial Intelligence (GEOINT). Provide Mobile Training Team (MTT) to military units requesting for OSINT support ranging from open source collection, social media research, social network analysis, media analysis and cyber network analysis. Created the first USCENTCOM Social Media Analysis course utilizing Facebook, Twitter and YouTube data sets as well as other foreign social media sites. The course is geared to gain a solid understanding of social listening tools such as Sysomos, Radian6, Netbase, Tracx, NM Incite, Buzz Metrics with emphasis on query creation and sentiment analysis. This course also includes knowledge of online web traffic & audience measurement tools such as Google Analytics, Omniture, Quantcast, ComScore, Topsy, Tweetreach, MIbazaar (tweetmap) and Compete. Familiarized intelligence analyst with 3rd party data visualization sites such Social Bakers and desktop programs like Tableau.

description: Worked as a CoIST instructor/ trainer developer under Stanley Associates/CGI. In charge of developing lesson plans, practical exercise scenarios, test validation and piloting multiple teaching approach for ICTMF instructors that are assigned to teach Company Intelligence Support Team (COIST). In charge of revising lesson plans for COIST, Intelligence Surveillance Reconnaissance (ISR), Targeting lethal and non-lethal applying both F3EAD and D3A methodology. Provide training to maneuver and support units in intelligence operations as a Mobile Training Team (MTT) instructor. Training consist of teaching targeting approach using lethal and non-lethal, plan and strategy for future operations, emphasis in Intelligence Preparation of the Battlefield (IPB) in urban and human terrain, use of unit personnel to conduct intelligence operations at the company level, Intelligence Surveillance Reconnaissance (ISR) planning and execution for the integration of all intelligence assets available to the unit, and conduct analysis and predictive analysis for future operations. Conduct fusion of systems and all Military Intelligence disciplines and ISR assets to achieve current and accurate situational awareness of the battle space. Use matrix and diagram tools to analyze enemy and friendly capabilities and Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTP) and offer course of action to Company Commanders to have a positive effect on unit's patrolling, convoy procedures and tactical maneuvers. Conducts training and participate in the Field Training Exercises (FTX) at Combat Training Centers (CTS), NTC, JRTC, JMRC in CONUS and OCONUS prior to deploying to combat theaters. Provide training in Tactical Ground Reporting System (TIGR) and Analysis and exploration of Information Sources Professional (AXIS PRO).

description: Provided Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) SME support to the Officer Education System (OES), Joint Intelligence Combat Training Center (JICTC), and US Army Intelligence Center of Excellent (USAICoE). Coordinate with the command to support the Soldiers training missions and provide a venue for Soldiers and staff to practice effective OSINT exploitation. Assist in the creation and publication of weekly 304th MI Bn OSINT Adversarial Topic Series on issues that are critical for Soldiers training requirements. Assist in the creation and publication of bi-weekly OSINT News Summaries that cover all Military Intelligence Military Occupational Specialties (MOS) and support current OSINT training requirements. Conducted the 1st 304th Military Intelligence Battalion OSINT Seminar held in Ft. Huachuca, attended by several representatives from the Intelligence Community (i.e DIA, INSCOM, etc.)

description: Deployed as a HUMINT Collection team leader in support of Operation Enduring Freedom, RC-S, Afghanistan. In charge of detainee operations and interrogation providing intelligence support to various task force such as the Weapons Intelligence Team (WIT), Media Exploitation Team (DOMEX), and Counter IED Exploitation Team (CEXC). Conducted missions with TF 3/73 Ranger Regiment as well as 1st and 7th Special Operations Group in RC-South, Afghanistan. Produced hundreds of intelligence reports alongside Special Operations units operating in RC-S, and Kandahar province. Worked closely with US AIRFORCE OSI, US Army CI Teams, OGA, and ISAF units using Military Source Operations resulted in multiple arrests of High Value Targets in Regional Command-South (RC-S). Increased source network in Regional Command-South Afghanistan. Provided detailed link charts and analysis products to tactical planners in support of counterterrorism operations throughout Afghanistan Areas of Responsibility (AOR) including counter narcotics operations, psychological operations and counter IED missions. Provided on-demand responses to requests for information from CENTCOM J2, G2, J2X and other NATO allies operating in Afghanistan. Conducted strategic analysis, HUMINT source reporting and elicitation procedures collecting raw data material in support of other NATO Intelligence allies. Worked directly with British Intelligence, Canadian Intelligence, Australian Intelligence, and US Marines Counter Intelligence Team element Regional Command-South, Afghanistan as well as Task Force operators operating in RC-South.

description: Provided all-source intelligence support to a joint headquarters responsible directly to the National Command Authority for strategic operations of national significance. Served as a core member of the Joint Planning Group (JPG), performing time-sensitive and enroute mission planning that enabled U.S. Special Operations Command’s elite units to conduct highly specialized, surgical, and sensitive operations worldwide. Provided Intel targeting support for operations against Afghan and Iraqi high value targets. As the senior intelligence officer aboard the airborne Command and Control platform during the initial assault into Afghanistan, fused all-source intelligence, dynamically re-tasked ISR assets and nominated targets for fires. Deployed as the lead DoD Intelligence officer to an Interagency Task Force that included the FBI and NYPD law enforcement.

description: Worked with the Defense Special Missile and Aeronautics Center (DEFSMAC/NSA) and NSA CSG rep to track Indications and Warnings (I&W) of impending Red and Grey space and missile launch activity. Fused SIGINT (COMINT), ELINT (telemetry), DSP (Infrared/thermal) data, IMINT, and OSINT to provide the Command Director and the Space and Missile Warning Center crews with intelligence needed to recommend a threat assessment to the National Command Authority. Monitored and reported on the launch preparations and movement of Russian Strategic Rocket Forces and ballistic missile and attack submarines. Tracked and reported on Russian long-range aviation activity and maintained situational awareness of ongoing conflicts in the Caucuses and elsewhere around the world. Tracked and reported all pending space re-entries that might be interpreted as an attack against North America and help the Intelligence Community track Russian and Chinese space surveillance capabilities. Monitored and reported Indications and Warnings related to the global Warning Problems and changes to the WATCHCON status.

description: • Cyber Threat Analyst responsible for all source/technical data collection and analysis utilizing tools such as Splunk, Netwitness, Wireshark, Maltego, and Analyst Notebook in order to synthesize a common operating picture of hostile intrusion-related activity for General Dynamics’ enterprise-level security posture. • Developing and maintaining new technical and nontechnical sources of information, threat research, advanced persistent threat (APT) actor profile development, historical, trend, link analysis, threat briefings, indicators and warnings development, and reporting for purposes of providing advanced warning of attacks to operations and users. • Expert knowledge of Splunk capabilities in server environment, including spunk language syntax, SIEM implementation, automated reporting and alerting, and dynamic pivoting for analysis. • Expert knowledge of Maltego, implementing as a core solution to intelligence analysis configuring data feeds from Netwitness, Domain Tools, Virus Total, and local data warehouse. • Conduct surface and dynamic analysis on captured malware to extract indicators of compromise and determine APT attribution. • Utilize open source research (OSINT) to collect, assess, analyze, and deploy indicators of compromise for known malware and other cyber threats to General Dynamics business units and other SOC customers. Constructed and maintain resident Wiki for APT and Malware intelligence.

description: • Trained in the complete array of Palantir capabilities in order to provide business systems analysis as the sole client- facing representative. • The FSR position required adhering to the core values of the Palantir model, one of which is Data Integrity. The software is designed to provide accountability at all levels of data entry and manipulation, which I was able to quickly understand the structure of and perceive its many applications. • Required to design and present demonstrations that would be for senior military or government personnel that reflected the software's various tools and applications, its dynamic ontology and analytic capabilities, and above all its ability to resolve data discrepancies across multiple disparate databases. • The FSR is responsible for all elements of the software development life cycle (SDLC), including training, data integration management, accounts access, server maintenance, and fault analysis.

description: • Responsible for researching, analyzing, writing, and disseminating the Threat Matrix; a daily summary of worldwide terrorist threats widely referenced by policy and decision makers, as well as intelligence and operational personnel, that is briefed daily in secure video teleconferences. • Production of the Threat Matrix required thorough review of pertinent and relevant terrorism reports and verification for accuracy within TIDE, so that all discrepancies could be analyzed and resolved immediately. • Additional products included; the Threat Review, a separate collateral version of the Threat Matrix; monthly, quarterly, and annual threat summary reports; and customized reports and searches tailored to meet the needs and requests of individual customers in the IC.

description: • Regular responsibilities were to conduct data integrity review of nominations to the FBI's Consolidated Terrorist Watchlist that required HUMINT and Biometrics driven data-mining and analysis within unclassified and classified systems pertaining to FBI, DOS, DOD, DHS, and other government agencies. • Rapidly promoted to advanced analyst and designated as Lead Subject Matter Expert (SME) for critical record processing that related directly to law enforcement queries and required thorough knowledge of FBI investigative subjects and coordination with field agents. My previous experience in SIGINT and counterterrorism analysis strongly contributed to my ability to identify mistakes and inconsistencies in TIDE and quickly and efficiently resolve them. • As Lead SME I was responsible to scrutinize hundreds of records individually, develop updated SOP, train subordinate SMEs, and coordinate with FBI field agents on discrepancy issues. Additionally developed new intelligence and business procedures for sensitive record processing and composed software enhancements for the client platform to streamline workflow and drastically increase productivity, and achieved expert proficiency in all systems and databases pertaining to the TIDE/TSDB nominations assessment process.

description: • Deployed with 3rd SFG to Afghanistan in support of OEF XV as Special Operations Team Alpha (SOT-A) SIGINT analyst and operator, providing direct action intelligence support to Special Forces teams at all stages of the intelligence process. • Our mission was to identify terrorist networks, designate high value targets (HVTs), compose SIGINT driven target packages, and support the Special Forces in a direct action role. This required utilizing active and passive collection platforms and a variety of analyst tools to focus on IED network disruption and target designated HVTs in the Wardak and Kabul areas. • Additionally I conducted analysis for the resident units in the area to coordinate target development and facilitate inter-unit cohesion. This analysis was specifically focused on data integrity by resolving redundancies and discrepancies in major databases that existed due to lack of communication between the resident military units and government agencies. It required inter-unit communication and coordination, entirely conceptualized and driven by myself and my SOT-A teammates. • Additional personal duties included constructing and certifying two temporary SCIFs, maintaining and trouble-shooting high-side connectivity, and managing team supply including highly sensitive COMSEC, over $5 million in team equipment, and $70k in operational funds.

description: • Operated in stateside counterterrorism analysis in support of the 82nd Airborne for OEF XIV by producing real-time target packages pertaining to HVTs in the unit's area of operations. • Organized and facilitated training exercises in signals guided (STG) missions on Ft. Bragg with every individual infantry company within the brigade. • Attended basic through advanced courses in SIGINT collection, data-mining and analysis comprised of mobile communications theory, pattern of life development, real-time target tracking, and operation of passive and active targeting devices. All levels of analysis focus heavily on data quality and require meticulous attention to detail in order to identify and resolve data integrity issues. Oversights in data integrity in SIGINT driven missions can easily result in the accidental merging or misidentification of terrorist identities.

description: Esri: 2000- Present • Senior federal account manager, Washington, D.C. office, Intelligence Team. Work with federal managers and Geographic Information Systems (GIS) specialists across all agencies in the Intelligence Community, including Military Intelligence organizations, to apply geospatial technology within GEOINT,SIGINT,MULTI-INT and Cyber environments. • Manage various Esri resources from contracting to technical support ensuring completion of government programs, missions and goals; on schedule and budget. Drawing upon professional relationships within the IC, successfully facilitated across government, Esri and other contractors to establish a complete geospatial capability within the SIGINT community. • Work with individual analytical teams to improve analytical methods and work flows using spatial analysis technologies. In addition to analytical methods development, provide advice as a Subject Matter Expert (SME) on GIS architectures and processes from requirements collection, planning, implementation to final product dissemination and reporting. • IC references can be provided upon request. Full Scope Polygraph. Managment training includes: The 7 Habits for Highly Effective Managers - Managing yourself, Leading Others, Uleashing Potential Crucial Conversations - Methods for enhanced communication

description: • 4/96 –10/00 NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Project Manager, Applied Information Sciences Branch. Manager of technology development projects and Geographer overseeing a team of contractors and civil servants on the development of new methods for imagery processing, analysis and delivery of information products to end-users of NASA data products. Conducted research in the application of airborne hyper spectral imagery. In addition to technical hands-on work, managed contracts and acquisitions of technical support as a Contracting Officer Technical Representative (COTR), managed a $5M budget and all aspects of program oversight and control. Presented results to top NASA Management, other Federal agencies. • 11/93 -4/96 NASA Headquarters, Earth Science Enterprise, Earth Science Applications Program Manager. Managed development of remote sensing applications programs across government and academia. Represented NASA on the Federal Geographic Data Committee, Coordination Committee working with other government agencies on development of geospatial standards, data collection and product dissemination across government. • 8/90-11/93 NASA, Space Station Program Office, Operations and Science Utilization Project Manager developing operational requirements and documentation in early station design and testing for effective station utilization. Established the first multilateral international space operations planning group with NASA's international partners.

description: Individually selected to spearhead the All-Source analysis effort for the Network Analysis Cell, CJ2 Kandahar Intelligence Fusion Center (KIFC), Combined Joint Task Force-10 (CJTF-10). Produced multiple Targeting Intelligence Packets/Target Support Packets, Social Network Diagrams, Interrogation Support Packets/ SDRs for detainee exploitation, and 400 RFIs incorporating GEOINT, SIGINT, Biometrics, TECHINT, and HUMINT in support of 10th Mountain and it’s subordinate units in Regional Command-South (RC-S) area of operations. Operated in coordination with OGA, NSA, NGA, DEA, DIA and FBI personnel to provide counterinsurgency support to Combined Joint Task Force-10 as the 10th MTN DIV (LI) Analysis and Control Element's (ACE) Master Analyst. Created, implemented, and supervised the Distributed Common Ground System – Army (DCGS-A) and ACE Block II system architecture for the RC-S Headquarters, applying first-ever employed designs to overcome regional-level challenges during combat operations. Personally directed the efforts of over 20 technical experts to field DCGS-A on the battlefield and commended by the ISAF CJ2 for excellence and technical expertise.

description: • Senior Intelligence Analyst and Senior Enlisted member of Joint Intelligence Center for Special Operations Command Central (SOCCENT). • Coordinated the development and provided quality control of intelligence products to support Army Special Forces Operational Detachments, Navy SEAL Teams, and Coalition Forces. • Managed production of Intelligence Summaries updating SOCCENT and Coalition SOF commanders with time-sensitive intelligence focusing on AOR wide terrorist organizations such as EAAQ, AIAI, JAM, IMU/IJU, and AQAM. • Fused information collected from tactical and national agencies into actionable intelligence products for SOF missions throughout the Area of Operations, developing target intelligence packets. • Managed the analytical efforts of seven service members to satisfy the Priority Intelligence Requirements and developed Intelligence Packets on specific High Value Targets and lethal aid related facilities. • Managed the J2 production schedule and products requirements. • Managed and maintained unit training programs forthe Korean Aerospace Operations Center (KAOC). • Directed intelligence wartime effort, matrixing intel experts across the KAOC as first ever enlisted Intelligence Duty Officer, position normally held by Capt or above. • Fused tailored ISR information into Strategy, Plans, and Operations divisions, responsible for prosecution of time sensitive targets prioritization and attack. • Principle advisor to commander for all intelligence support to Air Force Space Commanding General. • Performed in-depth space/missile threat research and analysis enhancing execution of SPACEAF weapon systems. • Conducted near-term and long-range analysis of global military intelligence for indications and warning. • Analyzed and maintained databases and products on adversary space reliance and terrestrial space targets. • Directed technical analysis of global adversary space launch and on-orbit space systems and capabilities.

description: Developed and produced intelligence products covering four provinces in northeastern Afghanistan. Recognized as the subject matter expert for Nangarhar Province in the 173rd Airborne Brigade during Operation Enduring Freedom. Worked with State Department, DEA, and British SAS teams that strengthened combined efforts in Nangarhar Province. Identified, developed, and created over 25 target packets resulting in the detention of numerous high value targets during Operation Enduring Freedom. Established the intelligence section of the Iraqi Army Mid-Euphrates Operations Center; resulting in the successful partnership between the 8th Iraqi Army Division intelligence officers and US forces during Operation Iraqi Freedom. Led a brigade level all source production section during Operation Iraqi Freedom, covering five provinces and consisting of joint service personnel specializing in HUMINT, SIGINT, MASINT, IMINT, and all-source analysts. Synchronized efforts with Special Operations, OGA, and DIA personnel.

description: Intelligence Fusion and operations support for coalition units directly engaged in Combat operations. Actively coordinates the fusing of operational and intelligence information to the supported unit and provides an operational perspective to the products for the supported commander. Work daily with the units Future Operations Planners to look forward and and help design specifically tailored network analysis/targeting packages ISO the units combat mission and threat enviroment. Responsible to the supported Commander to collect, analyze and fuse operational and intelligence information to assist the supported unit in Future Operations and targeting planning and conducting their assigned missions in the Conventional and Irregular Warfare Enviroment. Ability to create and analyze high-profile intelligence and anti-terrorism products for the Battalion, Brigade, Regiment, Division, MEF,Coalition Staffs and our interagency partners ISO the Counter Insurgency Fight in Afg. I deployed to eastern Afghanistan in May 2013, and SW Afghanistan in Jan 2014. After returning to Reston in Aug I was promoted to (Lead) Senior Operations Integrator for the RC East Team

description: With a Staff of 4 personnel I developed future and current operations and plans and was directly responsible for the coordination with all interagency partners to validate and justify these requirements. These exercises and requirements were ISO Marine Forces Reserve, New Orleans, La and their extensive Operational Commitments in Iraq, Afghanistan and also supporting USAF and USA Security Cooperation efforts in Central/South America and the Caribbean Basin. These Operations supported US Air Force South, US Army South and Marine Forces South, I worked almost daily with their planners to source Marines for these requirements. Worked directly with Marine Forces Command and HQMC in early 2010 ISO an urgent RFF from II Marine Expeditionary Force to support the Marines 24th MEU with Civil Affairs Marines for Operation Unified Response. The RFF called for a detachment of Civil Affairs Marines that also were French Speakers and needed them within 7 days. The Marines were sourced by my Office from units all over the US and were sent to Moorhead City NC before the MEU sailed. Worked with Manpower USMC (MMFA now MMIB) Force Augmentation Branch and Marine Forces Central Command on JMD issues IOT source specific Marine Corps billets ISO the ongoing fight in Afghanistan to USFOR-A and Marine Corps specific staffing to MarCent billets throughout Afghanistan and SW Asia. Only Representative for MarForRes in Washington DC with knowledge of DRRS(Defense Readiness Reporting System) and was the sole member of the Staff with access and ability to track, update and complete unit DRRS reporting.

description: •As Operations Chief I was responsible for assisting senior management in the efficient management of Operations and Training Plans to include, administrative, logistics and maintenance services. •Performed direct supervisory duties of all Operations and Unit staff members and Developed Future and Current Ops Training Plans and coordinated S3 Shop for Training,administrative and logistics planners for the Units extensive Operational Commitments in Iraq and Afghanistan ISO the War on Terror, Central and South America and the Caribean Basin ISO Air Force South, Army South and Marine Forces South. •Performed security manager duties as required, e. g., reviews of personnel clearances and security space requirements, technology and Facility Physical Security requirements for several Marine Corps Units in Washington, DC. •Taught unit level C-IED strategy and tactics to over 850 Marines and sailors deploying to Iraq and Afghanistan in conjunction with Pre Deployment Training (PTP) and Coordinated MRAP drivers training for Marines Deploying to Iraq and Afghanistan. • Implemented and monitored all support services, including procurement of Training, transport, travel , communications, engineering and information technology support and provision of local facilities and base service requirements. •Served as the I MEF G9 Chief during OIF 5 to provide humanitarian assistance to people of Iraq. •Developed, Coordinated and overseen the Units Worldwide Deployment Training Plans, ISO Iraq, Afghanistan, Central, South America, Caribean Basin and Africa.

description: •Solicited and coordinated support with other directorates/organizations, staff agencies and units within Central Command AOR. Had a firm understanding of financial/cost accounting as it relates to U.S. Government contracting and contracts. Senior Enlisted in Mobility section of the J4 directorate. Coordinated all enlisted schools and training for the Mobility section during this period. Thoroughly familiar with the Army Training Requirements and Resources System (ATTRS) and Army Knowledge Online (AKO).Directed, coordinated, supervised, train, and synchronize the work of the J4 (Mobility) section to ensure efficient and prompt actions; assists S4 in all aspects of logistics support to the J4 Directorate. Responsible to the Mobility section head for daily updates to Central Command Situation Reports (Sitrep), and mobility section JPERSTATS. Tracked vehicle movements with CentCom (JOPES) planners.

description: Notable Billets: 4th Intelligence Battalion, Bravo Co. •Active Clearance Top Secret / SCI (Department of Defense, United States Marine Corps) •Directly responsible for structuring and implementing two Humint Support Teams, HST-1 Aurora Colorado and HST-2 Chicago Illinois. Appointed as officer in charge(OIC) of HST-1. •Previously assigned to Imagery Interpretation Platoon. Conducted Imagery analysis in support to the Department of Defense and the Fleet Marine Corps. 2nd Reconnaissance Battalion Intelligence Chief Supervised, trained, and managed a diverse group of Intelligence Marines to include, SIGINT / HUMINT and IMINT personnel. •Supervised production of various intelligence products in support of combat operations during Operation Iraqi Freedom. •Directly contributed to the Intelligence preparation of the battlefield for the operations against Fallujah Iraq. •Developed and implemented IMINT Collections standards that were subsequently adopted as the theater standard. •Assisted human exploitation teams during combat missions in order to collect accurate information as well as directing sensitive sight exploitation efforts. •Served as the Battalion surveillance and reconnaissance asset manager, successfully implementing multiple surveillance system in a combat environment while developing extensive experience with Predator, Pioneer, Scan Eagle, Hunter, Dragon Eye, and Schweitzer. •Served as a technical advisor for Insitu / Boeing on the Scan Eagle project. •Conducted daily briefs for the Battalion / Regimental general staff. •Held the Intelligence Officer billet in the Combat Operations Center during combat operations. •Served as the Battalion liaison for other government agencies (OGA) and other defense agencies (ODA). Received special recognition from both. •Received awards for valor and performance in combat. United States Marine Corps Electronics Technician •Received multiple awards for excellence in performance.

description: Served as primary leadership force for all logistical activities supporting over 56,000 US service members in Fort Hood and Afghanistan. Directed 60-person team throughout 7 separate divisions in coordinating and directing transportation, distribution, maintenance, redeployment, supply, and sustainment operations supporting over 22 sub-organizations. Saved over $500 million in leading transfer of $36 million in military equipment to Afghanistan. Achieved reimbursement of over $137 million to US government for loan of more than $500 million in military equipment to coalition partner nations. Ensured optimal operation of supply and maintenance activities for 22 sub-organizations through exacting inspection of all on-site activities and equipment. Overhauled analysis of performance metrics; enabling executive-level decision-making and enhancing leadership efforts to demand accountability. Achieved Bronze Star for outstanding performance and Legion of Merit for honorable service.

description: Commander of Letterkenny Army Depot, with forward operations in Kuwait and support operations world-wide. Provides command & control of a maintenance depot consisting of over 1600 government civilians, 1100 contractors and 65 Soldiers. Serves as the installation commander providing command & control of an 18,800-acre installation with over 4M sq ft of facilities supporting more than 3500 personnel. Responsible for managing a $1.7 B Army Working Capital Fund executing over 3 million direct labor hours of maintenance, supply and base operations programs to achieve mission objectives. Responsible for performing depot maintenance and new build production for DOD Air Defense & Tactical Missile Ground Support systems, missiles, SOCOM, Force Provider, power generation, Biological Identification & Detection Systems, UAS, 5 Ton, HMMWV, RCV and MRAP vehicles and equipment.

description: Coordinated all logistics, distribution, planning, and policy / procedure development operations throughout Iraq as leader of 158-person team of ground, air, and sea logistics support specialists. Saved over $65 million through diverse initiatives to improve and streamline processes. Oversaw safe progress of over 110 convoys involving more than 3,500 vehicles per day. Established robust foundations for on-time, on-budget withdrawal of forces from Iraq through skilled development and implementation of nationwide retrograde plan. Reduced costs by over $67 million per year by streamlining maintenance support nationwide and eliminating over 700 positions, while ensuring 95% operational readiness. Secured over $26 million in savings by conducting in-depth cost-benefit analysis identifying most expense-efficient options for bottled water plant. Achieved Bronze Star for outstanding efforts in combat operations and Legion of Merit for performance excellence.

description: Promoted to lead transformation of senior headquarters overseeing command and control of on-site brigade training, resourcing, and deployment to modular force. Managed 7 warehouses, each with 5,000 SKU’s of repair components. Chosen by executive leadership to manage design and implementation of modular force. Reduced costs by more than $550,000 per year by transitioning Materiel Management Center from government civilian to contractor support and overhauling property book supply contract. Ensured on-time, on-budget execution of major brigade training initiative at Fort Irwin, California National Training Center. Achieved Meritorious Service Medal for outstanding performance.

description: Coordinated all aspects of maintenance and logistics, supply operations, medical support, transportation, and field services to over 8,000 staff members in 8 battalions and 6 distinct companies operating over 10,000 square miles as leader of 700-person military force in northern Iraq. Fuelled growth of unit from 300 team members and equipment worth $50 million to more than 700 and $95 million in key machinery, vehicles, and components. Directed delivery of fuel, water, supplies, and other mission-critical materials across over 350,000 miles of operations. Planned and orchestrated northern Iraq’s historic first free election, overseeing distribution of polling packages to over 100 locations. Forged partnership with Iraqi Olympic Committee for northern Iraq; sponsored development of Olympic-level volleyball team and led enhancements to Olympic training center. Coordinated transition of over 5,000 staff members from Fort Lewis to Mosul, Iraq and back.

description: • As an all-source intelligence analyst supporting Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force - Afghanistan (CJSOTF-A), worked with a team to research, analyze, present, and publish all source targeting analysis and intelligence production in support of operationally deployed special operations forces in the Special Operations Task Force - South (SOTF-S) area of operations. • Supported Targeting Effects Synchronization in support of future operations by identifying and developing actionable targets in AO. • Developed IPOEs in support of combined USSF/ANASOF missions being conducted in SOTF-S AO. • Developed enemy most likely/most dangerous course of action to support operational planning for Village Support Operations (VSO) expansion. • Traveled as required to SOTFs and forward units to conduct intelligence exchange and act as CJOSTF-A representative for briefings. • Coordinated with NGA, OGA, ORSA, DIA, COIC, MASINT, and TCAE analysts on a daily basis collaborating with other ISAF SOF elements for intelligence sharing. • Identified and track key personalities, named areas of interest, and compounds of interest to support targeting efforts. Additionally, served as the Senior All-source Intelligence analyst for the CJSOTF-A J2 External Areas of Influence (AI) Cell. • Conducted analysis of regional countries within the Middle East, South Asia, Central Asia, and East Asia that influence operations in Afghanistan. • Coordinated with ISAF, NATO, IJC, DoD, IC, and other counterparts to satisfy command objectives. • Conducted research and produce long-term strategic regional assessments on countries impacting the operational environment in and around Afghanistan.

description: • Senior Military Intelligence Analyst for North and Southeast Asia on various disciplines; geopolitical, military, insurgencies, and economic issues. • Reviewed, edited, planned, prepared, and published in-depth regional, strategic, and functional military intelligence studies and products. • Researched, reviewed, evaluated, analyzed, and integrated all-source intelligence data in order to assess and identify capabilities, vulnerabilities, opportunities, threats, and targets to develop warnings. • Manager of newly established intelligence organization that produced strategic and operational analytical work in support of military operations throughout the Pacific Rim. • Effectively exploited, analyzed, and evaluated large volumes of intelligence materials of a highly specialized, particularly sensitive character which resulted in a greater awareness of foreign policies and events. • Served as All Source Fusion Intelligence Manager for over 40 Intelligence Analysts ensuring administration, operational, and training requirements were met. • Managed the building of over 200 intelligence briefs in support of decision making of senior military officers on all regional threats and events. • Managed and supervised 15 intelligence analysts and reviewed all intelligence products before dissemination.

description: Duty Description: Senior Intelligence Sergeant for a Special Forces (SF) Company Area Operating Base (AOB) during Operation IRAQI FREEDOM (OIF) VI; provides timely all-source intelligence analysis and dissemination to the AOB staff and to six SF Operation Detachment - Alphas (ODA); schedules and monitors Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) for AOB and ODA target development; coordinates intelligence efforts with Conventional Forces (CF) and multiple Other Government Agencies (OGA); accountable for over $100,000 in property and equipment; responsible for health, welfare, and daily oversight of three junior NCOs in a combat environment - Targeting NCO, RFI Manager, AOB Collection Manager, AOB Security Manager, Map Custodian

description: Counterintelligence (CI) Special Agent Course- Army Intelligence Center and School as a senior counterintelligence member, led and managed a group of 6 military instructors, 25 civilian instructors and 10 government civilians responsible for teaching the Counterintelligence Agent Course, a 5 month course that’s responsible for training both Army and civilian agents in order to meet worldwide customer requirements. As the senior enlisted course lead I was responsible for welfare and personal care of all students numbering from 68 to 136 as well as the instructor cadre. Organized and maintained student curriculum plans as well as building classroom organization and systems maintenance. Responsible for the building security, internet security and ensuring all students held an appropriate clearance to attend the course and upheld all security regulations.

description: Provide test and evaluation, maintenance, repair and engineering services for Electro-Optic Visual Augmentation Systems (VAS) in support of the Warfighter Perform electronic technician work involving troubleshooting, repairing and measurement of complex electronic components and devices in a test/production environment. Maintain test and evaluation systems in accordance with standard operating procedures. Test, troubleshoot or repair test and data acquisition systems to diagnose/fix faults. Coordinate and schedule maintenance and repairs of test systems as required. Troubleshoot test theory and systems when testing anomalies occur. Collect test data, analyze results, and relate findings to specific operability issues Determine reliability of test systems and hardware and associated interfaces by assessing test data and failed hardware. Analyze electro-optic devices or systems interfaces to perform design, construct and testing of one of a kind electronic warfare and Chemical Detection Systems. Evaluate automated test stations and the capabilities of electronic data collection systems. Troubleshoot procedural methods and techniques associated with evaluation of Night Vision Devices, Thermal Imaging Systems, Laser Devices, ad Chemical Detection Systems. Execute electronic test and evaluation systems or sub-systems to evaluate new or modified electronic equipment. Evaluate adequacy of test equipment to repair, calibrate, or test electronic components.-Isolate, define, and characterize features of electronic problems. Recommend improvements to the reliability of systems and related equipment. Perform technical electronics engineering work to ensure operability and function of the item under test and test equipment. Create written documents (e.g., specifications, test requirement documents, drawings) to outline recommendations for modifications or alterations.

description: Coaching boys and girls in the development of their individual skills by providing knowledgeable teaching and mentoring in addition to the opportunity to play with and against great competition. Implementing character and leadership training through sports training I'm a firm believer that athletics can help guide today’s youth into leading confident and productive lives by being part of a team, accepting roles and learning that success comes from hard work. IBC provides an opportunity for players interested in playing sports at the college level to demonstrate their abilities to college recruiters at our College Exposure Events. Promote Southern Indiana boys and girls as well as teams and players from all around the Hoosier state, for statewide recognition, college scholarships and national promotion.

description: Manage small arms weapons systems and weapons accessories at Camp Atterbury. Test weapons systems for versatility, weapon performance, target acquisition, signature suppression and fire control. Test operational effectiveness of systems and make recommendations to the government that components are suitable and sustainable. Managed and monitor small arms weapons systems of the M4A1 Carbine, the M4A1 Carbine with attached M203-series Grenade Launcher, SCAR, Machineguns, Sniper Rifles, Shotguns, Pistols, and all mounted Crew Served Weapons. Responsible for identifying, fixing and fielding improved systems to provide improved operational readiness of small arms weapons for combat in Iraq and Afghanistan.

description: Engineered Special Operations Weapons (SOF) Modification Analysis and Quality Assurance. Performed Special Operations Weapons program efforts in system integration, research, development, testing, procurement and fielding of weapons systems and weapons accessories. Analyzed performance to optimize combat capability of the various subsystems of SOF weapons and weapons components. Collected analysis on weapons systems for versatility, weapon performance, target acquisition, signature suppression and fire control. Tested operational effectiveness of systems and made recommendations to the government that components are suitable, affordable and sustainable. Managed and strengthened systems application capabilities and limitations for development of improved operational capabilities. Weapons Systems may include but are not limited to the M4A1 Carbine, the M4A1 Carbine with attached M203-series Grenade Launcher, SCAR, SOF Machineguns, SOF Sniper Rifles, SOF Shotguns, SOF Pistols, and all mounted Crew Served Weapons. Analyzed the performance of SOF weapons systems and weapons accessories in various programs. Responsible for identifying, developing and fielding improved systems through enhanced durability and capability efforts to provide improved operational capability for SOF unique weapons. Assisted in User Assessment for MDNS-CWS Block III testing and procurement. Performed training on newly developed equipment for combat in Iraq and Afghanistan.

description: Oversaw and Managed a Indiana Army National Guard Armory / responsible for over $28.5 million dollars of equipment and facilities. Responsible for supervising Unit Operations, Training, Logistics and Administration. Managed all unit personnel training, medical and administrative records. Managed facility planning support for higher headquarters, including data collection, analysis, and reporting for space allocation, real property, facility planning. Developed Security laws, principles, systems, policies, and practices to provide routine Security services; analyzing security documents for accuracy and completeness; advising managers and employees on potential security issues and submitting documents to investigative/adjudicative bodies. Prepared (DOD) Department of Defense Risk Assessments and Safety Checks for all Military Pre-Combat and Training conducted on Mission, Equipment, Facilities and Environmental Hazards. Instructed workers individually and in groups, using various methods such as lectures, discussions, and demonstrations. Provided tactical and technical guidance to subordinates and professional support to both subordinates and superiors in accomplishment of their duties. Supervised and performed field and sustainment maintenance. Expert in writing, communication, computers, environmental awareness, outlines, management, military history and (MOS) Military Occupational Skills-specific leadership lessons. Supervised supply, services, and materiel management and logistics operations. Managed Unit Facilities, Unit Arms Room, Unit Supply Room, Facility Key and Lock custodian, Unit Safety NCO, Unit Movement Control Coordinator, Classified Documents Custodian, Unit Security Manager, Records Management Officer, Environmental Protection NCO, Terminal Area Security Officer, Network Security Officer, Unit Admin NCO, Unit Training NCO, Unit Medical NCO, Unit Ammo NCO, MSDS, OSHA, and HAZMAT.

description: Directly supervised staff assigned to Higher Headquarters. Mentored and provided leadership, technical advice and administrative guidance and instructions regarding programs, objectives, policies, procedures, mission analysis, course of action, problem solving and coordination of administrative activities. Identified training and development needs, established training plans, and provided formal and informal training as required. Established performance standards and evaluates subordinates. Received and resolved complaints and grievances on an informal basis; effects minor disciplinary measures such as warnings and reprimands; and recommended disciplinary actions in more serious cases. Developed employee performance standards and prepared employee performance evaluations. Planned and assigned non-routine work, sets priorities, and scheduled the completion of special projects; cross assigned and levels workload based on priorities, existing projects, and selective consideration of the difficulty of assignments and capabilities of employees. Enforced timeliness, quality, procedural, policy, and regulatory requirements. Provided advice and counsel or instruction to employees. Responsible for the command’s Antiterrorism, Force Protection and Physical Security AT/FP/PS Programs. Monitored the status of projects and actions and adjusts the Battalion Commanders priorities and suspense accordingly. Reviewed the work for overall effectiveness, clarity and conciseness. Reviewed and approved milestones for major inspections and audits from higher headquarters and inspections and staff assistance visits to Units. Monitored the Battalion Commanders training plan to ensure command and Companies are properly trained. Overall responsible for reviewing, revising, publishing and executing the Commander’s Critical Information Requirements, Serious Incident Reports, the command All Hazard Plan and Continuity of Operations Plan.

description: Advised and trained the Afghan Special Forces Company in the areas of intelligence, communications, fire support, logistics, operations and infantry tactics. Conducted independent counterinsurgency operations, tactically, operationally, and logistically. Managed executing military operations conducting call for U.S. close air support, indirect fire, and medical evacuation. Additionally I was employed as a PSD team member, Team leader and Assistant Team Leader, Coordinated with our host units planning, movement and operated completely autonomously when deployed. I coordinated the Staff planning and dissemination of mission critical information between not only US Army, Air Force and Navy Special Warfare and Coalition units, in pursuit of High Value Targets in all provinces of Afghanistan. Responsible for the critical role of liaising between the foreign unit and nearby U.S. units to ensure that each unit is aware of and can assist the other in their operations. Monitored and reported on the capabilities of the fledgling security force. Organized, planned, and executed over 200 SOF combined combat missions with SFODA, U.S Navy Seals, U.S. Air Force, FBI, CIA, and OGA while under fire. Resaponsible for capturing enemy soldiers and processing them for interrogation. Responsible for organizing and training over 300 Afghan Commandos conducting unilateral combat operations during Operation Enduring Freedom. Organized, Planned, and lead over 100 combat patrols throughout Southern Afghanistan locating caches and capturing over 120 truckloads of ammunition, weapons, and explosives. Devised and implemented training for a light Infantry Company on train the trainer programs. Responsible for finding, fixing and destroying over 20 Improvised Explosive Devises (IED). Developed and implemented instructor training programs for foreign soldiers before, during and after conducting SOF combat operations in Afghanistan.

description: Oversaw and Managed a Indiana Army National Guard Armory / responsible for over $28.5 million dollars of equipment and facilities. Supervising recovery operations on track vehicles, wheel vehicles and related activities including electrical wiring harness system repair/maintenance. Expert in writing, communication, computers, environmental awareness, outlines, management, military history and MOS-specific leadership lessons supervising soldiers engaged in supply, services, materiel management and logistics operations. Supervised management of materiel support functions in stock control and accounting, procurement, inventory control, and item financial management.

description: Contacts, interviews, and advises civilian personnel to obtain qualified applicants for enlistment into the Army. Contacts representatives of schools, public officials, personnel managers, parents of prospective applicants, religious and civil leaders, and others to present the Army as an employment and career opportunity. Advertising Establishes liaison with local radio, television, and newspaper agencies. Writes, edits, or presents material for use by local communications agencies. Discusses individual aims and goals to include security, personal aptitudes, training opportunities, job satisfaction and stability, advancement, prestige, and military life. Explains Army benefits including: medical care, dependent allowance, housing, reenlistment bonus, retirement program, military/civilian educational opportunities, travel, recreational benefits, and all similar programs. Evaluates applicants' occupational, educational, and psychological background to determine Army programs with specific individual appeal. Administers and scores screening physical examination, and enlisted screening test of applicants and counsels with regard to reasonable occupational aspirations within the Army. Counsels disqualified applicants. Assists in administration of Armed Services Vocational Battery (ASVAB) and explains results to school officials and students. Gathers individual data and prepares forms and documents incident to enlistment processing. Arranges for transportation, meals, and lodging for applicants where required. Maintains prospect card files, school program folders, and prospecting lists. Assists in market research and analysis of recruiting territory and makes appropriate recommendations to station commander.

Lead, trained, and supervised soldiers in operation and maintenance of radars and associated equipment. Responsible for over $18.5 million dollars worth of equipment. Lead and supervised unit maintenance on firefinder radars and ancillary equipment, and operator maintenance on organic communications equipment and vehicles. Established and maintained radio and wire communications; prepares for operation, and operated and maintained firefinder radars and associated equipment. description: Senior Triage Technician and ATS Site Lead ~ Lead Triage Technician for Afghanistan Captured Materials Exploitation (ACME) Lab, Bagram Air Field, Afghanistan. Received IED evidence recovered by EOD Teams, Weapons Intelligence Teams (WIT), SFAAT Teams, Joint and SOF support labs, ANSF and other Level 1 personnel. Safely assessed all evidence submissions for explosive threats employing diagnostic equipment and forensic techniques and identified and mitigated several procedural safety issues. Identified main-charge explosive materials, initiators, and switching components and ensuring the absence of “Trojan Horse” devices (booby-traps). Digitally photographed and cataloged IED components and related evidence and initiated the Level 2 WTI Exploitation & Analysis Tool (WEAT) report. Coordinated the evidence flow through forensic exploitation (ACME laboratories), Weapons Technical Intelligence (WTI) and when required, exploitation by Department of Defense facilities, towards final disposition at the Level 3 laboratories in the United States. Alerted Afghanistan Theater of Operations (ATO) authorities regarding new or emerging Tactics, Techniques and Procedures (TTPs) encountered during evidence examination. Provided plank members (EOD, RCP, LEPs, and OGA civilian personnel), classes, briefings, RFIs and special reports for proper documentation and evidence submission. Achieved enhanced proficiency with the CIDNE and WEAT database programs for all Triage lab personnel and trained three new triage technicians (one American and two German international members) in proper lab procedures.

description: Selected for expertise in course planning and development of course curriculum based on basic to advanced EOD skills and tactical skills required for CIED operations in support of the OEF Theater of operations. Provided training to Special Forces in EOD support and intermediate level CQB. Trained the Slovakian Armed Forces (SAF), EOD operators on CIED operations focused on IED Defeat and incident post analysis investigation. The program also included training to SAF Engineers to integrate with EOD forces within the safe limits of their battle space function.
